<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910703-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>910703-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Chelsea Industries Inc.:   Company Settles Lawsuits   On Biodegradability Claims</HL><DATE>07/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FLORIDA (FL)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)MINNESOTA (MN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)WISCONSIN (WI)</RE><LP>   Seven states settled their case against Chelsea IndustriesInc. over its degradability claims for its trash bagproducts.   New York State Attorney General Robert Abrams saidChelsea, the Boston-based maker of Good Sense and Handi-Bagbags, agreed to pay New York and the six other states,California, Florida, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Washington andWisconsin, $7,500 each and not make future &quot;degradability&quot;claims for its plastic trash bags. The company admitted nowrongdoing in the settlement.</LP><TEXT>   The Chelsea settlement is part of a continuinginvestigation headed by Mr. Abrams. Last week, Mobil Corp.agreed to pay $150,000 to settle a lawsuit filed by sixstates charging the company made misleading claims about thebiodegradability of its Hefty Trash Bags.   &quot;Chelsea's environmental claims were nothing more than amarketing ploy; their bags pose the same solid waste problemsas most other plastic bags,&quot; said Mr. Abrams. The statescharge that the treated trash bags, which are supposed todegrade faster when exposed to the sun and other elements,are usually left buried in landfills, where they provide noenvironmental benefits.   Chelsea officials couldn't be reached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>